---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Metallicity effects on stellar colors and luminosities";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Metallicity effects on stellar colors and luminosities</h1>

    <p>
      <strong>Metallicity</strong> ([M/H] or [Fe/H]) significantly affects stellar properties including color, luminosity, and evolutionary timescales. More metal-rich stars are redder (at fixed luminosity) and follow different evolutionary tracks than metal-poor stars.
    </p>

    <h2>Effects on distance indicators</h2>
    <p>
      Many standard candles (Cepheids, TRGB, RR Lyrae) show metallicity dependence in their absolute magnitudes. Accurate distance measurements require either:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Controlling for metallicity via color measurements (e.g., TRGB color-magnitude calibration)</li>
      <li>Selecting mono-metallicity populations</li>
      <li>Applying metallicity correction formulas calibrated empirically</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>TRGB case study</h2>
    <p>
      Chazov et al. (2026) demonstrate that the TRGB in JWST F090W becomes fainter at metallicities above [M/H] ≃ -0.57, with the transition occurring at (F090W-F150W)₀ ≃ 1.65 mag<sup><a href="/pages/chazov_2026_trgb_jwst">1</a></sup>. Accounting for this metallicity-color relation is critical for precise distance measurements to galaxies with mixed-metallicity stellar populations.
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Chazov M. I., et al. (2026). arXiv:2603.11160.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
